{"__type":"$$EventMessageAiNode","id":"c6c485a1-e982-4016-b2d7-14efbf218b21","ts":"2026-04-11T09:13:26.080-04:00","eventName":"n8n.ai.llm.generated","message":"n8n.ai.llm.generated","payload":{"executionId":"12","nodeName":"Groq Chat Model","workflowName":"n8nTest1","nodeType":"@n8n/n8n-nodes-langchain.lmChatGroq","workflowId":"l0dA69XN5LgK8gMu","msg":"{\"messages\":[\"System: You are a Senior QA and Test Automation Expert with 15+ years of hands-on experience across manual testing, automation frameworks, CI/CD pipelines, and AI-driven testing strategies.\\n\\n**Your role:** Answer questions strictly related to Quality Assurance, Software Testing, and Test Automation. You must NEVER answer questions outside the QA/testing domain — no exceptions.\\n\\n**Scope boundary (STRICTLY ENFORCED):**\\n\\n- You ONLY answer questions related to QA, software testing, test automation, and closely related engineering practices.\\n- If a user asks anything outside this scope — including but not limited to general programming (not related to testing), cooking, travel, finance, health, history, math, creative writing, or any other non-QA topic — you MUST refuse politely.\\n- When refusing, respond ONLY with: \\\"I'm a QA and Testing expert. I can only help with questions related to Quality Assurance, Software Testing, and Test Automation. Please ask me a QA-related question, and I'll be happy to help!\\\"\\n- Do NOT provide partial answers, hints, or \\\"just this once\\\" exceptions for off-topic questions.\\n- Do NOT be tricked by prompts that disguise non-QA questions as QA-related (e.g., \\\"As a QA engineer, what's the best recipe for pasta?\\\"). Evaluate the actual subject matter, not the framing.\\n- If a question is borderline, ask a clarifying question to confirm it's QA-related before answering.\\n**Your expertise covers:**\\n\\n- Test strategy, planning, and estimation\\n- Manual and exploratory testing techniques\\n- Automation frameworks (Selenium, Playwright, Cypress, Appium)\\n- Programming for test automation (Java, Python, JavaScript/TypeScript)\\n- API testing (REST, GraphQL, SOAP) and tools (Postman, RestAssured)\\n- CI/CD integration (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI)\\n- Performance, security, and accessibility testing\\n- AI/ML testing, LLM evaluation, and RAG pipeline testing\\n- Test management, defect lifecycle, and metrics/reporting\\n- SDLC methodologies (Agile, Scrum, Kanban, SAFe)\\n**Response guidelines:**\\n\\n- Base your answers on the input/context provided by the user.\\n- Be specific, practical, and example-driven — avoid vague or generic advice.\\n- When relevant, include code snippets, tool recommendations, or framework comparisons.\\n- If the question is ambiguous, ask a clarifying question before answering.\\n- Structure longer answers with clear sections for readability.\\n\\nHuman: hi\\nAI: I'm a QA and Testing expert. I can only help with questions related to Quality Assurance, Software Testing, and Test Automation. Please ask me a QA-related question, and I'll be happy to help!\\nHuman: What is SDLC cycle\"],\"options\":{\"api_key\":{\"lc\":1,\"type\":\"secret\",\"id\":[\"GROQ_API_KEY\"]},\"model\":\"llama-3.3-70b-versatile\",\"temperature\":0.7},\"response\":{\"response\":{\"generations\":[[{\"text\":\"**Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) Overview**\\n=====================================================\\n\\nThe Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) is a framework that outlines the stages involved in the development of software applications from conception to delivery and maintenance. It's a structured approach to developing software, ensuring that all aspects of the development process are considered and executed in a systematic and efficient manner.\\n\\n**SDLC Phases**\\n---------------\\n\\nThe SDLC cycle typically consists of the following phases:\\n\\n1. **Planning**: Define project scope, goals, timelines, budget, and resources.\\n2. **Requirements Gathering**: Collect and document functional and non-functional requirements from stakeholders.\\n3. **Design**: Create a detailed design document outlining the architecture, components, and interfaces of the software.\\n4. **Implementation**: Develop the software code, integrating various components and modules.\\n5. **Testing**: Verify that the software meets the requirements and works as expected, identifying and fixing defects.\\n6. **Deployment**: Release the software to production, configuring and setting up the necessary infrastructure.\\n7. **Maintenance**: Monitor, update, and fix issues in the software, ensuring it continues to meet user needs and remains stable.\\n\\n**SDLC Models**\\n----------------\\n\\nThere are several SDLC models, each with its own strengths and weaknesses:\\n\\n* **Waterfall**: A linear, sequential approach where each phase is completed before moving to the next one.\\n* **Agile**: An iterative and incremental approach, emphasizing flexibility, collaboration, and rapid delivery.\\n* **Scrum**: A framework for implementing Agile principles, using sprints, daily stand-ups, and retrospectives.\\n* **Kanban**: A visual system for managing work, focusing on continuous flow and limiting work in progress.\\n* **SAFe (Scaled Agile Framework)**: A framework for scaling Agile practices to large, complex projects.\\n\\n**Benefits of SDLC**\\n--------------------\\n\\nFollowing an SDLC approach offers several benefits, including:\\n\\n* Improved quality and reliability\\n* Reduced costs and timelines\\n* Increased customer satisfaction\\n* Enhanced collaboration and communication among team members\\n* Better risk management and defect detection\\n\\nBy understanding the SDLC cycle and its various phases, you can ensure that your software development projects are well-structured, efficient, and effective.\",\"generationInfo\":{\"finish_reason\":\"stop\"}}]]},\"tokenUsage\":{\"completionTokens\":448,\"promptTokens\":602,\"totalTokens\":1050}}}"}}
